BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Davis R Users' Group
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260217T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260217T200000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51754758569924
DESCRIPTION:D-RUG\, our local R Users' Group\, meets weekly to facilitate 
 learning and using the R software language. R users from all domains are i
 nvited to bring their R-specific coding problems and share their experienc
 e with other members of the community. Meetup formats include everything f
 rom group discussion and mini-workshops to coworking sessions. D-RUG is ru
 n by volunteer Coo[R]dinators including UC Davis data scientists and gradu
 ate students dedicated to growing and strengthening the R community.\n\n \
 n\nToday's session is open-forum format to foster a communal\, co-working 
 environment. Come hang out and chat\, work on your own\, seek and give hel
 p\, and make friends.\n\n \n\nD-RUG meets Thursdays in person from 10 AM t
 o 12 PM at the DataLab Classroom (Shields Library room 360) on the UC Davi
 s campus. \n\nSign up for our mailing list to get the most up to date info
 rmation\, including a Zoom link to join us virtually if you can't make it 
 in person. Learn more about D-RUG on our website.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/davis-r-users-group-2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:DataLab Office Hours (in person)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260217T210000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260217T220000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50755967513283
DESCRIPTION:DataLab offers free in person drop-in office hours during whic
 h UC Davis researchers can obtain data science help and advice on working 
 with their data. During these short\, just-in-time sessions we meet with f
 aculty\, students\, postdoctoral scholars\, and staff from all domains acr
 oss the University. Depending on the nature of your question and our avail
 ability\, it may be possible to schedule a longer follow-up consultation a
 fter your office hours visit.\n\nAppointments are not required. Please com
 plete the brief office hours intake form ahead of time to help us connect 
 you with the right expert for your question.\n\nCommon office hours help t
 opics include:\n\nOpen Source Programming (R\, Python\, Julia\, etc.)Repro
 ducible research computing and data scienceResponsible and ethical data sc
 ienceData gathering\, organization\, databases\, and experimental designDa
 ta analysis\, statistics\, and explorationData visualizationMachine learni
 ng and neural networksText mining and natural language processingGeospatia
 l sciencesRemote and high performance computingComputational pedagogy… a
 nd more!Please note that drop-in office hours are not offered during Unive
 rsity holidays\, academic breaks and finals week. Summer schedule varies. 
 DataLab may only be accessed during Shields Library's business hours. Clic
 k here for detailed directions to DataLab.\n\nNote: We are unable to provi
 de support for assigned coursework (homework assignments\, class projects\
 , etc.) during office hours. If you need such help please contact your ins
 tructor or TA for assistance. If you need help with technical problems suc
 h system administration and hardware issues\, check out the the UC Davis S
 erviceHub and/or contact your departmental IT.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/copy-of-datalab-office-hours-
 in-person
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Covered: Faculty Author Talks by Javier Arbona-Homar and Bettina N
 g'weno
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260218T013000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260218T033000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51817137369841
DESCRIPTION:Join us for an evening with UC Davis faculty authors Javier Ar
 bona-Homar and Bettina Ng'weno as part of Covered\, a monthly event series
  celebrating recent books from the College of Letters and Science.\n \n\nJ
 avier Arbona-Homar\, associate professor of American Studies and Design\, 
 discusses Explosivity\, a sweeping investigation of the Bay Area’s lands
 cape through episodes of militarism\, racialized capitalism and historical
  erasure. Drawing on archival research\, oral histories and site visits\, 
 he traces how past detonations continue to shape public memory and geograp
 hy.\n Bettina Ng’weno\, professor of African American and African Studie
 s\, shares from No Place Like Home in a New City\, an intimate account of 
 how residents of Nairobi resist anti-urban ideologies to build life\, belo
 nging and new urban futures amid rapid redevelopment. \n\n\nCovered: Spotl
 ighting Faculty Authors in Letters and Science is co-sponsored by the Jan 
 Shrem and Maria Manetti Shrem Museum and the UC Davis Library.
LOCATION:Manetti Shrem Museum
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/covered-faculty-author-talks-
 february2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Workshop: Cleaning and Reshaping Data in R (part 1 of 2)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260219T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260219T200000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51818563851045
DESCRIPTION:Cleaning your data is often the most time-consuming part of re
 search. In this 2-part workshop for researchers using R\, we will move pas
 t coding basics to tackle the complexities of real datasets and learn effe
 ctive data preparation workflows.\n\n \n\nWe'll practice how to efficientl
 y identify potential problems with structure and data types\, and write sc
 ripts to effectively convert and correct these issues. We'll discuss the p
 rinciples of "tidy data\," ensuring your datasets are structured perfectly
  for your analysis and visualization. Then we’ll take a deep dive into t
 he stringr package for text processing\, and the lubridate package for han
 dling dates and times. You’ll also learn how to use tidyr and dplyr to r
 eshape data and join linked datasets.\n\n \n\nWhether you're gathering you
 r data by hand\, scraping the web\, or importing text files\, this trainin
 g will help expand your R coding skills to turn your data into analysis-re
 ady files with confidence and reproducibility.\n\n \n\nAfter completing th
 is training\, learners should be able to:\n\nInspect data files to determi
 ne how best to load them into R\;  Identify and convert features to approp
 riate data types\;Use the “stringr” package clean and extract data fro
 m text\;Use regular expressions to describe patterns in text\; Use the “
 lubridate” package to parse dates and times\;Identify features of a "tid
 y" dataset\;Describe the advantages and disadvantages of tidy data\;Use th
 e "tidyr" package to reshape data\;Describe what a join is\;Compare differ
 ences between an inner join and left join\;Use the "dplyr" package to join
  two data sets on a common column\;and learn where to go to learn more! \n
 \nThis workshop is offered in person only. All members of UC Davis are wel
 come to register. Advance registration required. Please plan to attend bot
 h sessions:\n\nPart 1: February 19\, 2026 (10 AM- 12 PM)Part 2: February 2
 6\, 2026 (10 AM - 12 PM) \n\nPrerequisites\n\nThis workshop is intended fo
 r motivated learners from all domains at UC Davis who want to hone their e
 xisting R skills. Thus\, we won't cover introductory R questions during th
 is session. Participants should be comfortable with basic R syntax\, and h
 ave the latest version of R and RStudio pre-installed and running on their
  laptops. If you're new to R\, or want to brush up\, we suggest you start 
 with our "R Basics" workshop curriculum.\n\n \n\nCan’t attend this event
 ? Materials from prior UC Davis DataLab workshops are available on DataLab
 's website. Check out our workshop schedule for other upcoming trainings.\
 n\n \n\nQuestions? Contact datalab-training@ucdavis.edu.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/workshop-w2026-intermediate-r
 -data-cleaning-part1
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
