BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:maptimeDavis: Making Maps in R
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260220T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260220T200000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51508978106036
DESCRIPTION:Location: DataLab Classroom - room 360 Shields Library\n \n\nD
 escription: In this workshop\, participants will learn how to use several 
 options for composing maps in R.\n \n\nAfter completing this chapter\, lea
 rners should be able to: Apply popular mapping workflows to create maps wi
 th spatial data\; assess which workflow works best in different situations
 \; apply cartographic best practices to a map composition in R\n \n\nConce
 pts Covered: R\, Cartography\, Programming\, Data Vizualization\n \n\nSpea
 ker: Michele Tobias\n\nMichele Tobias is a geospatial data scientist with 
 a background in geospatial methods for ecology. Michele earned her PhD fro
 m UC Davis in Geography where she studied California’s sandy beach ecosy
 stem with traditional phytosociological methods and innovative remote sens
 ing tools and was a postdoc at the UC Davis Information Center for the Env
 ironment. In her current position as a geospatial data scientist at UC Dav
 is DataLab\, she applies geospatial tools to new avenues of research acros
 s disciplines.\n \n\nPrerequisites: For the best experience\, we recommend
  learners have the following skills before taking this workshop: an introd
 uctory understanding of programming in R (for example\, you are familiar w
 ith how to load libraries\, load common data formats like a CSV\, and are 
 comfortable running basic commands). See DataLab’s R Basics Workshop for
  help\; an introductory understanding of spatial data (for example\, you a
 re familiar with the difference between raster and vector data). See DataL
 ab’s \,a href="https://ucdavisdatalab.github.io/workshop_spatial_data_fo
 rmats/">Spatial Data Formats Workshop for help\; (recommended) review the 
 concepts (first section) of DataLab’s Cartography for Academic Publicati
 ons Workshop.\n \n\nSoftware Required: To fully participate in this worksh
 op\, learners should download and install R and RStudio on their laptop be
 fore the workshop begins.\n \n\nPlease RSVP.
LOCATION:DataLab\, 360 Shields Library
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/datalab-making-maps-in-r
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Collaborative Data Science Office Hours (virtual)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260223T210000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260223T220000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50756015391870
DESCRIPTION:DataLab and colleagues from research computing and statistical
  service units across UC Davis offer weekly free virtual office hours duri
 ng which UC Davis researchers can obtain help and advice on working with t
 heir data. During these short\, just-in-time sessions we meet with faculty
 \, students\, postdoctoral scholars\, and research staff from all domains 
 across the University to discuss their research challenges.\n\nRegister in
  advance for the Zoom link. This helps us connect you to the right expert 
 for your question.\n\nIn addition to DataLab\, the collaborative data scie
 nce office hours are supported by:\n\nBiostatistics (Clinical and Translat
 ional Science Center\, CTSC)Computational Research Data Service (College o
 f Letters & Science)High Performance Computing (HPC) CoreResearcher Servic
 es (UC Davis Library)Stat Lab (Department of Statistics)Common office hour
 s help topics include:\n\nOpen Source Programming (R\, Python\, Julia\, et
 c.)Reproducible research computing and data scienceResponsible and ethical
  data scienceData gathering\, organization\, databases\, and experimental 
 designData analysis\, statistics\, and explorationData visualizationMachin
 e learning and neural networksText mining and natural language processingG
 eospatial sciencesRemote and high performance computingComputational pedag
 ogy… and more!Please note that drop-in office hours are not offered duri
 ng University holidays\, academic breaks and finals week. Summer schedule 
 varies based on availability.\n\nNote: Office hours are intended for short
  "just in time" research support. If you require extensive assistance we m
 ay refer you a recharge service\, upcoming funding/project calls\, and/or 
 other resources. We are unable to provide support for assigned coursework 
 (homework assignments\, class projects\, etc.) during office hours. If you
  need such help please contact your instructor or TA for assistance. If yo
 u need help with technical problems such system administration and hardwar
 e issues\, check out the the UC Davis ServiceHub and/or contact your depar
 tmental IT.
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/copy-of-collaborative-data-sc
 ience-office-hours-virtual
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
