BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Creative Writing Series: Maria Kuznetsova\, Fiction
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T233000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260409T003000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51534087526177
DESCRIPTION:Please join us for the next event in the 2025-2026 Creative Wr
 iting Series: a reading and Q&A featuring novelist Maria Kuznetsova!\n\nTh
 is event is free and open to all\, and will be available in person and liv
 estreamed.\n\n \n\nMaria Kuznetsova was born in Kyiv\, Ukraine\, and moved
  to the United States as a child. She is the author of the novels Oksana\,
  Behave! and Something Unbelievable. An alum of the UC Davis master’s pr
 ogram in creative writing\, she now lives in Auburn\, Alabama\, with her f
 amily\, where she is an associate professor of creative writing at Auburn 
 University. She is also the fiction editor of the Southern Humanities Revi
 ew and her work appears or is forthcoming in dozens of literary journals i
 ncluding One Story\, The Yale Review\, Southern Review\, Threepenny Review
 \, and The Sun.\n\n \n\nThe Creative Writing Series is presented by the UC
  Davis Department of English\, Creative Writing Master of Fine Arts Progra
 m\, and the UC Davis Library.\n\nThe views expressed in this series\, incl
 uding descriptions and biographies\, are those of the speakers and not mea
 nt to represent the views of any other person or institution.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 205
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/creative-writing-series-maria
 -kuznetsova-novelist
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Publish Your Work: From Idea to Impact — Traditional and Alterna
 tive Options
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260409T200000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260409T210000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52322769236438
DESCRIPTION:Publish Your Work: From Idea to Impact\, Traditional and Alter
 native Options is a Zoom workshop that will give you an overview of (1) tr
 aditional publishing options\, such as peer-reviewed journals\, and (2) al
 ternative publishing options\, such as preprints\, open methods\, and open
  data.\n\nWhether you’re going to be publishing for the first time or yo
 u’ve published many times in the past\, join us to learn more about open
  research\, avoiding predatory publishers\, selecting an appropriate journ
 al\, and how to publish your research outputs in ways that go beyond the t
 raditional journal article.\n \n\nNo previous experience is required. All 
 disciplines are welcome.\n\nPlease register for the Zoom link. \n\nThis si
 x-workshop series is a collaboration between the library's Scholarly Commu
 nications Program\, the Researcher Services department\, and Blaisdell Med
 ical Library. For any questions\, please contact the Scholarly Communicati
 on Officer Michael Ladisch (mladisch@ucdavis.edu). Check our events calend
 ar for more publishing workshops.
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/workshop-publish-your-work
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:AI Literacy & Logic: 1-day intensive course
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T233000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52340792785132
DESCRIPTION:A 198 course for College of Letters & Science majors.\n\nThe l
 andscape of the academic and professional world is shifting. Whether you a
 re an aspiring historian\, a budding chemist\, or a future sociologist\, A
 I is no longer a "tech" skill—it’s a foundational literacy.\n\nDevelop
 ed through a collaboration between the UC Davis College of Letters & Scien
 ce and DataLab\, this 1-unit intensive course is designed to unveil Artifi
 cial Intelligence. We’ve stripped away the dense math and complex coding
  to give you a conceptual\, high-level understanding of how artificial int
 elligence systems work\, why they matter\, and how to make them work for y
 ou.\n\nWhy Enroll?\n\nIn a single day\, you will move from being a passive
  AI user to a critical\, strategic collaborator. This training is specific
 ally curated for L&S students to ensure you graduate with the competitive 
 edge needed for the rapidly evolving\, AI-driven workplace.\n\nNo technica
 l background? No problem. This course has no prerequisites. It is designed
  for thinkers\, writers\, and researchers across all liberal arts and scie
 nce disciplines.\n\nThe curriculum is divided into four deep-dive modules:
 \n\nHow AI Thinks\nUnderstand the "brain" of the machine. We’ll explore 
 the theories of language and cognition that allow Large Language Models (L
 LMs) to function\, and provide a framework for evaluating their potential 
 and limits.\n\nHow to Use AI Responsibly\nAI isn't a magic wand—it’s a
  tool with a history and consequences. We discuss the environmental and so
 cietal impacts\, how to ensure the veracity of AI results\, and why reprod
 ucibility is the cornerstone of ethical tech.\n\nHow to Talk with AI\nMast
 er the art and science of prompt engineering. Learn what happens behind th
 e scenes when you send a prompt. Develop sophisticated strategies to get t
 he exact results you need.\n\nModule 4: How AI Talks with You\nA look at t
 he future of AI implementation. From simple chatbots to complex autonomous
  "Agents\," learn how AI is being embedded into systems and how to evaluat
 e its activity.\n\nBy the end of this one-day course\, you will be able to
 :\n\nDefine "AI" and distinguish it from traditional statistics and data s
 cience.\n\nIdentify whether a real-world problem is suitable for an AI sol
 ution.\n\nDevelop advanced prompting strategies that produce reliable\, us
 eful results.\n\nCritically interrogate your own engagement with AI and it
 s impact on our society and environment.\n\n \n\nApply Now\n\nThis intensi
 ve\, one-day course will be offered five times during Spring Quarter 2026.
  You only need to signup for one date. \n\nTime: 9:00 AM – 4:30 PM (with
  a break for lunch)\n\nCredits: 1 Unit\n\nCRN & location: Will be emailed 
 to accepted and confirmed registrants.\n\nEligibility: Open to all student
 s with a major in the College of Letters & Science.\n\nPriority: Registrat
 ion priority is given to Seniors (4th years) and students graduating in Sp
 ring or Summer 2026. Other students in the College of Letters and Science 
 are encouraged to register and will be admitted as space permits.
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/ai-literacy-logic-spring-2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
