BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Covered: Faculty Author Talks by Lisa G. Materson and Corrie Decke
 r
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260415T003000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260415T023000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51817323649794
DESCRIPTION:Join us for an evening with UC Davis faculty authors Lisa G. M
 aterson and Corrie Decker as part of Covered\, a monthly event series cele
 brating recent books from the College of Letters and Science.\n \n\nLisa G
 . Materson\, associate professor of history\, traces civil rights activist
  Ruth Reynolds’ deep involvement in the movement for Puerto Rico’s ind
 ependence in Radical Solidarity\, offering a nuanced account of political 
 allyship\, anti-colonial struggle and cross-racial collaboration. \n Corri
 e Decker\, associate professor of history\, examines how colonial courts a
 nd ethnographers in 20th century East Africa transformed complex rites of 
 passage into simplified “puberty rites" in The Age of Sex: Custom\, Law\
 , and Ritual in Twentieth-Century East Africa\, reshaping legal understand
 ings of childhood\, adulthood\, gender and sexual maturity. \n \n\nCovered
 : Spotlighting Faculty Authors in Letters and Science is co-sponsored by t
 he Jan Shrem and Maria Manetti Shrem Museum and the UC Davis Library.
LOCATION:Manetti Shrem Museum
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/covered-faculty-author-talks-
 by-lisa-materson-and-corrie-decker
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:From Idea to Impact: Publishing Your Work — Demystifying the Man
 uscript Submission Process
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260416T200000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260416T210000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52332214449432
DESCRIPTION:Publishing research in an academic journal is a critical step 
 in every scholar’s journey. However\, it can be a very complex and intim
 idating landscape\, especially for those who have limited experience with 
 the process. This workshop will provide an overview of the manuscript subm
 ission process including\, manuscript preparation\, guidance on citing AI 
 tools\, the peer review process\, and how to go about choosing copyright t
 erms when uploading your paper.\n \n\nNo previous experience is required. 
 All disciplines are welcome. \n\nPlease register for the Zoom link.\n\nThi
 s six-workshop series is a collaboration between the library's Scholarly C
 ommunications Program\, the Researcher Services department\, and Blaisdell
  Medical Library. For any questions\, please contact the Scholarly Communi
 cation Officer Michael Ladisch (mladisch@ucdavis.edu). Check our events ca
 lendar for more publishing workshops.
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/demystifying-the-manuscript-s
 ubmission-process
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Creative Writing Series: Summer Farah\, Poetry
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260416T233000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260417T003000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51534123490206
DESCRIPTION:Please join us for the next event in the 2025-2026 Creative Wr
 iting Series: a poetry reading and Q&A featuring poet\, essayist and zine-
 maker Summer Farah!\n\nThis event is free and open to all\, and will be av
 ailable in person and livestreamed.\n \n\nSummer Farah is a Palestinian Am
 erican writer\, editor\, and zine-maker from California. She is the author
  of The Hungering Years (Host Publications\, 2026) and the chapbook I coul
 d die today and live again (Game Over Books\, 2024). Her essay "From Witne
 ss From Speech From Image: On Etel Adnan’s The Arab Apocalypse and There
 sa Hak Kyung Cha’s Dictee" received a 2025 Krause Essay Prize honorable 
 mention. Summer is a member of the Radius of Arab American Writers and the
  National Book Critics Circle. She is calling on you to recommit yourself 
 to the liberation of the Palestinian people each day.\n \n\nThis event is 
 co-sponsored with the Department of Middle East/South Asia Studies.\n \n\n
 The Creative Writing Series is presented by the UC Davis Department of Eng
 lish\, Creative Writing Master of Fine Arts Program\,\nand the UC Davis Li
 brary.\n\nThe views expressed in this series\, including descriptions and 
 biographies\, are those of the speakers and not meant to represent the vie
 ws of any other person or institution.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 205
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/creative-writing-series-summe
 r-farah-poetry
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
