BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Davis R Users' Group
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260512T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260512T190000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51754758590415
DESCRIPTION:D-RUG\, our local R Users' Group\, meets weekly to facilitate 
 learning and using the R software language. R users from all domains are i
 nvited to bring their R-specific coding problems and share their experienc
 e with other members of the community. Meetup formats include everything f
 rom group discussion and mini-workshops to coworking sessions. D-RUG is ru
 n by volunteer Coo[R]dinators including UC Davis data scientists and gradu
 ate students dedicated to growing and strengthening the R community.\n\n \
 n\nToday's session is open-forum format to foster a communal\, co-working 
 environment. Come hang out and chat\, work on your own\, seek and give hel
 p\, and make friends.\n\n \n\nD-RUG meets Thursdays in person from 10 AM t
 o 12 PM at the DataLab Classroom (Shields Library room 360) on the UC Davi
 s campus. \n\nSign up for our mailing list to get the most up to date info
 rmation\, including a Zoom link to join us virtually if you can't make it 
 in person. Learn more about D-RUG on our website.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/davis-r-users-group-2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:DataLab Office Hours (in person)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260512T200000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260512T210000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50755967521485
DESCRIPTION:DataLab offers free in person drop-in office hours during whic
 h UC Davis researchers can obtain data science help and advice on working 
 with their data. During these short\, just-in-time sessions we meet with f
 aculty\, students\, postdoctoral scholars\, and staff from all domains acr
 oss the University. Depending on the nature of your question and our avail
 ability\, it may be possible to schedule a longer follow-up consultation a
 fter your office hours visit.\n\nAppointments are not required. Please com
 plete the brief office hours intake form ahead of time to help us connect 
 you with the right expert for your question.\n\nCommon office hours help t
 opics include:\n\nOpen Source Programming (R\, Python\, Julia\, etc.)Repro
 ducible research computing and data scienceResponsible and ethical data sc
 ienceData gathering\, organization\, databases\, and experimental designDa
 ta analysis\, statistics\, and explorationData visualizationMachine learni
 ng and neural networksText mining and natural language processingGeospatia
 l sciencesRemote and high performance computingComputational pedagogy… a
 nd more!Please note that drop-in office hours are not offered during Unive
 rsity holidays\, academic breaks and finals week. Summer schedule varies. 
 DataLab may only be accessed during Shields Library's business hours. Clic
 k here for detailed directions to DataLab.\n\nNote: We are unable to provi
 de support for assigned coursework (homework assignments\, class projects\
 , etc.) during office hours. If you need such help please contact your ins
 tructor or TA for assistance. If you need help with technical problems suc
 h system administration and hardware issues\, check out the the UC Davis S
 erviceHub and/or contact your departmental IT.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/copy-of-datalab-office-hours-
 in-person
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Covered: Faculty Author Talks by Claire Goldstein and Michael Dyla
 n Foster
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260513T003000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260513T023000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51817344074825
DESCRIPTION:Join us for an evening with UC Davis faculty authors Claire Go
 ldstein and Michael Dylan Foster as part of Covered\, a monthly event seri
 es celebrating recent books from the College of Letters and Science.\n \n\
 nClaire Goldstein\, professor of French and Italian\, discusses In the Sun
  King’s Cosmos\, her engaging study of how comets shaped scientific\, po
 litical and cultural imagination in 17th century France. \n Michael Dylan 
 Foster\, professor of East Asian Languages and Cultures\, presents the exp
 anded edition of The Book of Yokai\, exploring the folklore\, history and 
 ongoing cultural life of Japan’s supernatural beings. \n\n\n\n \n\nCover
 ed: Spotlighting Faculty Authors in Letters and Science is co-sponsored by
  the Jan Shrem and Maria Manetti Shrem Museum and the UC Davis Library.
LOCATION:Manetti Shrem Museum
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/covered-faculty-author-talks-
 by-claire-goldstein-and-michael-dylan-foster
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:AI Literacy & Logic: 1-day intensive course
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260516T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260516T233000
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52340792788207
DESCRIPTION:A 198 course for College of Letters & Science majors.\n\nThe l
 andscape of the academic and professional world is shifting. Whether you a
 re an aspiring historian\, a budding chemist\, or a future sociologist\, A
 I is no longer a "tech" skill—it’s a foundational literacy.\n\nDevelop
 ed through a collaboration between the UC Davis College of Letters & Scien
 ce and DataLab\, this 1-unit intensive course is designed to unveil Artifi
 cial Intelligence. We’ve stripped away the dense math and complex coding
  to give you a conceptual\, high-level understanding of how artificial int
 elligence systems work\, why they matter\, and how to make them work for y
 ou.\n\nWhy Enroll?\n\nIn a single day\, you will move from being a passive
  AI user to a critical\, strategic collaborator. This training is specific
 ally curated for L&S students to ensure you graduate with the competitive 
 edge needed for the rapidly evolving\, AI-driven workplace.\n\nNo technica
 l background? No problem. This course has no prerequisites. It is designed
  for thinkers\, writers\, and researchers across all liberal arts and scie
 nce disciplines.\n\nThe curriculum is divided into four deep-dive modules:
 \n\nHow AI Thinks\nUnderstand the "brain" of the machine. We’ll explore 
 the theories of language and cognition that allow Large Language Models (L
 LMs) to function\, and provide a framework for evaluating their potential 
 and limits.\n\nHow to Use AI Responsibly\nAI isn't a magic wand—it’s a
  tool with a history and consequences. We discuss the environmental and so
 cietal impacts\, how to ensure the veracity of AI results\, and why reprod
 ucibility is the cornerstone of ethical tech.\n\nHow to Talk with AI\nMast
 er the art and science of prompt engineering. Learn what happens behind th
 e scenes when you send a prompt. Develop sophisticated strategies to get t
 he exact results you need.\n\nModule 4: How AI Talks with You\nA look at t
 he future of AI implementation. From simple chatbots to complex autonomous
  "Agents\," learn how AI is being embedded into systems and how to evaluat
 e its activity.\n\nBy the end of this one-day course\, you will be able to
 :\n\nDefine "AI" and distinguish it from traditional statistics and data s
 cience.\n\nIdentify whether a real-world problem is suitable for an AI sol
 ution.\n\nDevelop advanced prompting strategies that produce reliable\, us
 eful results.\n\nCritically interrogate your own engagement with AI and it
 s impact on our society and environment.\n\n \n\nApply Now\n\nThis intensi
 ve\, one-day course will be offered five times during Spring Quarter 2026.
  You only need to signup for one date. \n\nTime: 9:00 AM – 4:30 PM (with
  a break for lunch)\n\nCredits: 1 Unit\n\nCRN & location: Will be emailed 
 to accepted and confirmed registrants.\n\nEligibility: Open to all student
 s with a major in the College of Letters & Science.\n\nPriority: Registrat
 ion priority is given to Seniors (4th years) and students graduating in Sp
 ring or Summer 2026. Other students in the College of Letters and Science 
 are encouraged to register and will be admitted as space permits.
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/ai-literacy-logic-spring-2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
